{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:39:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13790"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13790"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.03,0.71,0.11,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6408"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58467"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6408"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43883"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1371"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12621"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42934"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58467"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of an intensely itchy rash. He reports small blisters appearing on his elbows, knees, and buttocks. The patient has been experiencing intermittent abdominal discomfort and loose stools for the past few months. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. Skin examination reveals grouped erythematous papules and vesicles on the extensor surfaces of his elbows and knees, as well as on his buttocks. Some areas show excoriations and crusting due to scratching.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Psoriasis","Scabies","Dermatitis herpetiformis","Bullous pemphigoid","Contact dermatitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Edermatitis herpetiformis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by intensely pruritic papulovesicular eruptions, typically occurring symmetrically on extensor surfaces such as elbows, knees, and buttocks. The associated gastrointestinal symptoms (abdominal discomfort and loose stools) further support this diagnosis, as dermatitis herpetiformis is strongly associated with coeliac disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with well-demarcated, erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales, rather than the vesicular eruptions described here. While it can be itchy, the intense pruritus described is more characteristic of dermatitis herpetiformis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScabies\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with intense itching, especially at night, and with burrows in characteristic locations such as between the fingers, on the wrists, and in the genital area. The distribution of the rash in this case is not typical for scabies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid\u003C/strong\u003E usually affects older individuals and presents with large, tense blisters. The small vesicles described in this case are more consistent with dermatitis herpetiformis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically localised to areas of exposure to an irritant or allergen and would not explain the gastrointestinal symptoms. The distribution on extensor surfaces is more suggestive of dermatitis herpetiformis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDermatitis herpetiformis is triggered by gluten, a protein found in wheat, barley, and rye. Removing gluten from the diet reduces immune activation that causes the skin eruptions. Patients should strictly adhere to a lifelong gluten-free diet, which not only helps manage skin symptoms but also reduces the risk of intestinal damage and potential complications of untreated coeliac disease. Whilst a gluten-free diet can eventually lead to remission of DH symptoms, it may take months or even years for symptoms to fully resolve after initiating the diet.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dermatitis herpetiformis is characterised by intensely pruritic papulovesicular eruptions, typically on extensor surfaces.","Dermatitis herpetiformis is strongly associated with coeliac disease and responds to a gluten-free diet."],"references":["Renal T, Hervonen K, Salmi T. Dermatitis Herpetiformis: An\u00a0Update on\u00a0Diagnosis and\u00a0Management. Am J Clin Dermatol. 2021; 22: 329\u2013338."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43883"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13790"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20731"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20731"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ydYdGqjvFR9V7gX9SYi0oFUNVqvWUZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ydYdGqjvFR9V7gX9SYi0oFUNVqvWUZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}